Two night business trip
Overall an average experience.  Pros were a large room with microwave and larger mini fridge, nice breakfast area, nice courtyard and pool, proximity to highway and eating choices in walking distance.  Cons were noise (room on street side), Keurig machine did not work in room, room had no real dresser for clothes, and the furniture needed updating, and personal preference the bed was too firm for my liking,  Would stay again for the convenience but among HIE properties this was just average overall.

Fantastic service, clean rooms, great smoothies!
We stopped here because we were going to spend the day at Six Flags. My son got a fever just before check-in, so we ended up spending two days/nights just hanging out in the hotel. I ran around a lot, getting food for the sick boy and taking care of stuff - and this place is close to lots of quick food, which is all my son wanted to eat. And during all my up-and-down, in-and-out lobby visits, staff was friendly, professional and helpful.  If my son had to get sick during our LA vacation, I'm so glad it happened here! Room was immaculate and modern with comfortable beds and no noise (except when someone passed in the hallway). We had GREAT service in every way - and I especially loved the breakfast smoothies!

Budget room for budget price
Booked last minute as flight changed and needed to be close to airport/car rentals. Check in was quick and staff were friendly. Room was clean but dated. Beds were comfortable. Pool was small but good enough for a dip to cool down.  No tea/coffee facilities in room. No safe in room. Very noisy ( no double glazing) but air con ok. Area a little run down. There is an airport shuttle bus but be prepared to wait (45 minutes for us) was just sorting out taxis when it arrived.  It’s good enough for some to sleep on a budget whilst waiting for flight, but no more than that.

Good Stay One Night
We stayed one night and everything was great.  Staff was good, the room was nice, the traffic noise was not bad.  The bed was comfortable. In comparison to the Holiday Inn Express in Carpinteria, everything is bigger and better, the room, the pool area and the breakfast. Curiously, neither place had potatoes in the breakfast, and each had both pork and turkey sausage.  But the breakfast here was well stocked with many choices, including real oatmeal and a pancake machine.  The breakfast room is spacious.

Second review -- because no AC during a heat wave, and no refrigerator, is just unacceptable
I stayed at this hotel in March of 2019. At that time, the street noise was the issue and the hotel's response to my comments then was that "noise" was dependent on each individual's sensitivity. I never bothered to tell them that loud garbage trucks in the middle of the night would exceed anyone's tolerance for noise.  But here I am in late September, and it is over 90 degrees Fahrenheit outside, and this room is a furnace! HOW is it possible that in 2019 a hotel in the middle of a major US city does not have air conditioning, nor a refrigerator to keep bottled water cooled in a room? I never turned on the television -- you can promptly replace that with a refrigerator! Meanwhile, the staff tells me the building is over 100 years old and is not outfitted for air conditioning

Just ok
We stayed here for a week. Wish we had done more research about the area as having now been we wouldn’t have chosen union square to stay. Hotel staff were all very friendly. Room was clean but felt dated and very small. Bathroom was nice. No air con was a nightmare as it was very hot, there was a small fan but was very noisy. WiFi in room was practically non existent and very annoying. Very noisy all through the night. Homeless all around union square and the hotel. Fabulous shops in union square and cable cars very close to hotel. We also walked to tourist places, exploring painted ladies, fisherman’s wharf, pier 39, Mrs Doubtfire house, Lombard street etc. took about 45 mins or so. Had a great time in San Francisco but we wouldn’t stay at this hotel again.

Not bad. Lot of commercial jets
The rooms are nice, the staff was great,  there is significant noise from the over flying jet aircraft one right after the other. This might be an issue for some.   A lot of them early morning, not bad at night.

It ticked all my boxes.
I arrived around nine at night having without a reservation, having driven from the Inland empire on my way to the Mexico border. I needed a motel near the airport so i could return the rented car and then take the metro to the border.   The Motel is  at the end of the runway on the other side of the fence and planes literally skim the roof on landing, it is an experience to behold, I loved it it it was like being on a movie set. I only stayed a night and my room was clean enough. Given its location you would expectit to have been really noisy, but I did not find this to be the case. Sure I could feel the downdraft from the planes kind of like skock waves, but as i was only staying one night i enjoyed the novelty.  I would certainly recommend the experience.

This was the first time my boyfriend had visited San Francisco and I wanted to book a hotel in the city but convenient since we didn't have a car. This hotel was a short block from the Bart/Muni stations and Cable Car stop. Lots of shops and restaurants around the area, very lively if that's what you like. But I was hesitant since I read a lot of negative reviews about the area. It's True...turn around the corner and there's homeless people, drug addicts, and fighting going on. It didn't bother us but some of the homeless are kind of forward. Just don't be rude or confrontational. Most of the time, we just walked by and didn't make eye contact. We stayed in Rm 403 (corner room in front) which allowed a lot of noise in but we didn't mind. Front desk staff was great except for an older Caucasion women who wasn't very friendly but not mean. Overall, I would totally come back.

Saw a show at the Warfield and Hotel Bijou is walking distance.  This area of The Tenderloin has been cleaned up considerably in the last 10-15 years, but it still has its "character".  Our room at the Hotel Bijou was clean and comfortable, and with a window overlooking Eddy towards Market we were able to get fresh breeze and an appropriate soundtrack of the city (shutting the window to minimize the outside noise was optional).  Staff at the hotel were excellent.  The bar/restaurant downstairs is a neat feature although it did not appear to be staffed that night.  Walking distance to a number of restaurants and bars, so not really problematic, and they did have a minimal breakfast buffet for $8 which I felt was reasonable.

Here’s the good:
Great customer service. Friendly and helpful staff. They were always very accommodating and quick to respond. Great restaurant for dinner with good wine (it’s expensive tho). Good, free coffee available 24/7. (They had hazelnut creamer, which is my favorite.) Rooms come with smart tv’s. We prefer Netflix over cable, so it was nice to have the option to watch whatever we want. Good selection of toiletries. Toothpaste, mouth wash, and slippers were nice to have on top of the normal set of hotel toiletries. Location was really close to everything we needed.

Here’s the bad:
SF has homeless everywhere, but it’s particularly thick right there. I could hear everything from our 2nd floor room and every night was noisy. It smelled of urine in either direction. Stay there long enough, you’ll get to see why. For the most part, homeless keep to themselves, but I don’t recommend standing outside at all.
WiFi was terrible. Worst than most hotels. So forget about working. Forget about watching Netflix. I stayed for 1 week and ended up using 3 different rooms. Shower broke in the 1st, shower water wasn’t hot enough in the 2nd, and I gave up by the 3rd. Water pressure in all 3 rooms were meh.. I noticed toiletries varied from room to room. Our 1st room didn’t have a shower cap, the 2nd and 3rd room didn’t have toothpaste, etc. Their breakfast is cheap but you get what you pay for.

Ehhh....
I didn’t know that there was going to be a bunch of people screaming on the side of the hotel. Also, there was a huge flash with a loud gun shot that occurred at night which was also not on the brochure. Receptionist also didn’t inform me that there was going to be a deposit of the same amount the reservation was for so do expect a double charge if you book here.

A Bijou in The Tenderloin
Cleanliness, staff & service, property conditions & facilities, room comfort
Saw a show at the Warfield and Hotel Bijou is walking distance.  This area of The Tenderloin has been cleaned up considerably in the last 10-15 years, but it still has its "character".  Our room at the Hotel Bijou was clean and comfortable, and with a window overlooking Eddy towards Market we were able to get fresh breeze and an appropriate soundtrack of the city (shutting the window to minimize the outside noise was optional).  Staff at the hotel were excellent.  The bar/restaurant downstairs is a neat feature although it did not appear to be staffed that night.  Walking distance to a number of restaurants and bars, so not really problematic, and they did have a minimal breakfast buffet for $8 which I felt was reasonable.
